               <interp inst="t18431127-259" type="date" value="18431127"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18431127-259-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-259-18431127 t18431127-259-offence-1 t18431127-259-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18431127-259-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-259-18431127 t18431127-259-offence-2 t18431127-259-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>259. <persName id="def1-259-18431127" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-259-18431127" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-259-18431127" type="surname" value="HARMAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-259-18431127" type="given" value="SOPHIA"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">SOPHIA HARMAN</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted for<rs id="t18431127-259-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18431127-259-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18431127-259-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="pocketpicking"></interp> stealing 5 sovereigns, 2 half-sovereigns, 3 shillings, 2 sixpences, and 2 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. notes, the monies of <persName id="t18431127-name-1374" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1374" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1374" type="surname" value="MARSDEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1374" type="given" value="GEORGE EAGLES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1374" type="occupation" value="brewer"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18431127-259-offence-1 t18431127-name-1374"></join>George Eagles Marsden</persName>, and others, from the person of <persName id="t18431127-name-1375" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1375" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1375" type="surname" value="SIMPSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1375" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1375" type="occupation" value="clerk"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18431127-259-offence-1 t18431127-name-1375"></join>William Simpson</persName>; and </rs>
                  <persName id="def2-259-18431127" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-259-18431127" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-259-18431127" type="surname" value="REDDING"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-259-18431127" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN REDDING</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18431127-259-offence-2" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18431127-259-offence-2" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18431127-259-offence-2" type="offenceSubcategory" value="receiving"></interp>, for feloniously receiving the same, and being accessory after the fact.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1377" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1377" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1377" type="surname" value="SIMPSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1377" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM SIMPSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to George Eagles Marsden, and two others, brewers, at Lewisham. On the 2nd of Oct., between nine and ten o'clock at night, I left the Horse and Groom, Blackheath-hill, somewhat the worse for liquor—I had two 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. notes, six or seven sovereigns, and some silver, all in my left hand waistcoat pocket, in a bag—I got home about ten—I went down Blackheath-hill, and up Lewisham-lane—when I got home I missed my money—I was accosted on my way by a female—I cannot exactly recollect what took place—I was not accosted by more than one female, to my know<lb></lb>ledge—I had taken the money on my masters' account.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> I believe you advertised the 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. notes? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I had bills printed, offering 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. reward for their recovery—not for the conviction of the thief—I have not traced the notes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1378" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1378" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1378" type="surname" value="COOK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1378" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>ANN COOK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an unfortunate girl, but am now in an asylum at Bethnal-green—I know the prisoner Harman—she is a girl of the town, and lived in Mill-lane at the time with the male prisoner—I was in Lewisham-road about ten o'clock on 2nd Oct., and saw Mr. Simpson—Harman was with me—Mr. Simpson was walking along the road, rather tipsy—Harman went</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184311270176"></xptr>
               <p>up to him—he <hi rend="italic">shoved</hi> her away, telling her he did not want anything to say to her—he gave her a fourpenny-piece—it was a moonlight night—he then came and took hold of my hand, and asked me to go down the road with him—I did not, as Harman <hi rend="italic">shoved</hi> me away, and said she should do better with him than me—they stood about ten minutes together, and then she came away—they were about ten yards from me—she had him round the waist for about ten minutes—she then went down the road, and I went with her—she said she had two sovereigns, and if I came down she would give me a quartern of gin—I went with her to the Clock House, Broadway, Deptford—she went in there to the prisoner Redding, as she told me—I waited outside the door—I saw two pieces of white paper in her hand as she went into the Clock House—she put them down her bosom—they were rolled up—when shr came out of the Clock House she said she had given it to <hi rend="italic">Johnny</hi> Redding—I thought she meant the two sovereigns—I saw Redding come out of the Clock House almost directly after her—he walked on the other side of the road—Harman had said she had no more money, before she saw the prosecu<lb></lb>tor—we had some rum at the Fountain, at the corner of Mill-lane, after we left the Clock House, a little after ten—she changed one shilling for the rum—she said she had no money at half-past eight, when I first met her, when she got a quartern of gin on trust at Lewisham-road, at the Ordnance Arms—I saw her next morning, and she said <hi rend="italic">Johnny</hi> was gone out to buy a pair of Wellington boots—I told of this about a week after—I had not heard of the reward then.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What did she change? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> She changed a sovereign at the Swan, Blackheath-road, before she went to the Clock House—I have been living with a young man for about ten years—I am now twenty-four years old—I have walked the streets for the last eight weeks, as he is in trouble for beating a policeman—he is at Maidstone, and was tried here—I do not think he has been gone three months—I have not walked the streets for nine or ten months—my name is Cook, but they call me Byrne, sometimes, which is my grandmother's name—I was never called <hi rend="italic">Match Kit</hi>—a relation of mine is called so—I have been in trouble for beat<lb></lb>ing the police and taking a drop of gin, nothing else—I was sent to Maidstone gaol for three months—a person named Richards was there at the same time for taking a bed-gown—my mother sent me there then—I was charged with stealing it, and sent to Maidstone for two months—I have been in custody three or four times, but have not been in trouble for these three years—the prosecutor was not a moment holding my hand—Harman would not let him—I made him no answer; <hi rend="italic">Sophy spoke</hi> to me too quick—I went out that night about eight o'clock from Mill-lane—I left there with the prisoner—she walked rather before me, as she did not like <hi rend="italic">Johnny</hi> to see me with her—I walked with her till ten o'clock, and went straight home after leaving her—I was at home a little after ten—we both went home together, and I went to bed—I informed the policeman of this about five days after, and before that told <hi rend="italic">Carry Hawkins</hi>, who lives in the same house as me—the police have looked after her, but cannot find her—I did not see her that night—I saw her the night after the robbery.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WILKINS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> For the last ten years you lived with the young man? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—his name is Prebble—he is a boiler-maker—he has been in custody three times for beating the police—he was absent fourteen months once; at one time he was confined four months, and was sent from here six months—the fourteen months was five or six years ago—I when he is away I go out for my living on the town, but not all the time, as I went to the Union—he took me back when he came out of prison all the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184311270177"></xptr>
               <p>three times—I was never charged with robbing a deaf and dumb man of a watch—I never heard of it—Mr. Molineaux put me in the asylum—I am to return there—my yonng man comes out about March—he was tipsy, and <hi rend="italic">shoved</hi> against a policeman—I was present—I was not tipsy—I tried to get him away from the policeman, but did not strike him—I have not been living at a brothel—I charged a Mr. Martin with an assault—I did not tell her I would do for the prisoners, and get 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., nor anything of the kind—I did not appear against her, as I went on the wrong day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is Mr. Molineaux the superintendent? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I was about eight years old when I was at Maidstone about the gown—I was charged with stealing about five years ago—since that I have not been in custody, except for getting drank—I only saw Harman change one sovereign that night.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You were charged with stealing about five years ago? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, the young man with me was also taken—the Magistrate dismissed the charge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1379" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1379" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1379" type="surname" value="BROOKS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1379" type="given" value="STEPHEN"></interp>STEPHEN BROOKS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman.</hi>) On the night of 6th Oct. I saw the witness in Child's-lane, Lewisham, with another female, who I did not know, at ten o'clock—she was on the way from the Horse and Groom to Marsden's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1380" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1380" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1380" type="surname" value="EASTGATE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1380" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>MARY EASTGATE</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at the Ordnance Arms—I know Harman and Cook, and remember them having a quartern of gin at my house one evening, which they did not pay for—it was between nine and ten o'clock early in Oct.—I cannot say what day—I heard of this robbery a few days after.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was not Cook the person who asked for trust? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I think it was, but cannot say.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1381" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1381" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1381" type="surname" value="FIGG"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1381" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN FIGG</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at the Swan, Blackheath-road. One Monday evening, at a quarter past eleven o'clock, I gave change for a sovereign to a person who was with Cook, and who I believe to be the female prisoner, but I have no knowledge of her, except serving her that time.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Ton know it was the other female took the change? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, I know it was the prisoner—I can<lb></lb>not positively say it was her—I believe so—I had seen Cook before—I did not suspect them to be women of the town—I do not know <hi rend="italic">Carry</hi> Hawkins.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What makes you believe the prisoner to be the person? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have no particular reason for saying so, only from what Cook said to me about a week or eight days after—I have no recollection of her features.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1382" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1382" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1382" type="surname" value="HOOPER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1382" type="given" value="LOUISA"></interp>LOUISA HOOPER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an apprentice to Mr. Clay, a draper, Broadway, Deptford. On the morning of the 5th of Oct. the female prisoner came to look at a cloak—she said she could not have it until her husband returned with the money—she then went away, and returned in about an hour with five or six sovereigns, which she gave to me and took the cloak to show her husband—she afterwards came back again and paid 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for the cloak—I gave her the remainder of the money—next day she came with the male prisoner and purchased a dress—she said she would call her husband to have his opinion upon it—he came, and said he was no judge—the amount of her bill that day was 19<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 9<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I saw her again next day, and she bought a bonnet for 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you known her for any time? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I had seen her before—I believe she was a customer at the shop—I never served her but once before—she then gave me silver—the value of the article she then bought was 16<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. or 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>—I do not know of her having had other articles at our shop—I knew where she lived.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1383" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1383" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1383" type="surname" value="M'LELLAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1383" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL M'LELLAN</persName>
                  </hi>, <hi rend="italic">watchmaker, Deptford-bridge.</hi> On Saturday, the 7th</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184311270178"></xptr>
               <p>of Oct., Redding came to my shop, and paid me 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for a watch which he had bargained for before, and this was the balance due—the price of the watch was 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>—he had paid me the sovereign on the Thursday evening, I think.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1384" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1384" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1384" type="surname" value="CLOTHIER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1384" type="given" value="JOSEPH LOCKYER"></interp>JOSEPH LOCKYER CLOTHIER</persName>
                  </hi>, <hi rend="italic">clothes salesman, Flagon-row, Deptford.</hi> On the morning of the 3rd of Oct. I sold Redding a sort of printed velveteen coat for 13<hi rend="italic">s</hi>—he gave me a sovereign—I gave him 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. out.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1385" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1385" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1385" type="surname" value="SLATER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1385" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN SLATER</persName>
                  </hi>, <hi rend="italic">shoemaker, Church-street, Deptford.</hi> I sold Redding some boots about six weeks back—it was the second day of Croydon fair, I think, on a Tuesday—he paid me 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>—Martin was with him, and he borrowed 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. of Martin—they went out together.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1386" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1386" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1386" type="surname" value="MARTIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1386" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES MARTIN</persName>
                  </hi>, <hi rend="italic">Mill-lane, Deptford.</hi> I have known Redding about eight years, and Harman three or four months—they both lived in my house, Harman in a ready-furnished room, and Redding was a nightly lodger, and slept along with my brother—he never slept with Harman to my knowledge—mine is a lodging-house—I was with Redding when he bought the pair of second-hand boots—it was on a Tuesday, I believe, about seven weeks ago, about Croydon fair time—I had heard him say a long time before that he would buy a pair of Wellington boots—I was with him the same day when he bought the second-hand coat of Clothier for 13<hi rend="italic">s</hi>—I gave Maxwell, who lives next door to me, a coat which Redding had given me to take care of the night he was taken—I did not know there was any thing in it then—it was not the coat I had been with him to buy—I have lent him money from time to time, 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., or 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and so on—he got his living by collecting old clothes, which he sold in Petticoat-lane—he borrowed 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. of me to pay for the boots, and he paid me again the same day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WILKINS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Has he not generally paid you the same day when you have lent him money at other times? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—the clothes busines is sometimes very profitable.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When did he go to the Clock House to live as pot-boy? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Before last Christmas—he was in the clothes line before that, ever since I have known him—he continued pot-boy till he hurt his hand about four months ago—he then went collecting old clothes again.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1387" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1387" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1387" type="surname" value="MAXWELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1387" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS MAXWELL</persName>
                  </hi>, <hi rend="italic">Mill-lane, Deptford.</hi> On the 10th of Oct. I received from Martin this coat and a gown-piece wrapped in it—I afterwards gave them to Lovell.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1388" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1388" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1388" type="surname" value="LOVELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1388" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>BENJAMIN LOVELL</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant R</hi> 15.) I received these from Maxwell—I took Harman into custody on the 10th of Oct., and told her I wanted her on suspicion of robbing a gentleman in the Lewisham-road—she said she knew nothing about it—I did not search her—I knew where she lived—I searched her lodging, and there found this cloak—she said she had been to Brighton with <hi rend="italic">Johnny</hi> Redding—I went to the station about one o'clock in the morning, and found Redding there in custody—I told him I should charge him with receiving money, knowing it to be stolen, from <hi rend="italic">Sophy</hi>—he said he did not know her—I told him from the woman he was living with—he said he was not living with any woman—I said, "I mean <hi rend="italic">Soph</hi> "—he said, "I don't know her"—I said the girl he went to Brighton with—he said if he had been to Brighton it had nothing to do with me—he had this coat on.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1389" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1389" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1389" type="surname" value="WHITE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1389" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN WHITE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable R</hi> 180.) I took Redding into custody on the 10th of Oct., at the Clock House, Deptford, about ten o'clock in the evening—I asked if he knew any thing of the prisoner <hi rend="italic">Sophy</hi>—he said "Yes"—I asked if he did not live with her—he said "No"—I took him to the sta<lb></lb>tion, searched him, and found this watch—I asked where he got it—he said</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184311270179"></xptr>
               <p>he bought it of a Jew—I found in his pocket 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. and a weighing machine—I knew him by sight—he was pot-boy at the Clock House once, and I have seen him since he left there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1390" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1390" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1390" type="surname" value="M'LELLAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1390" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL M'LELLAN</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> This is the watch he bought of me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1391" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1391" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1391" type="surname" value="HOOPER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1391" type="given" value="LOUISA"></interp>LOUISA HOOPER</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> This gown-piece and cloak are like what I sold Harman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18431127-259-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
